OrderedDict([(u'@bibcode', u'2002JGRA..107.1012N'), (u'metadata', [OrderedDict([(u'@origin', u'AGU'), (u'@type', u'general'), (u'@primary', u'True'), (u'@alternate_journal', u'False'), (u'creation_time', u'2011-10-04T17:07:05'), (u'modification_time', u'2011-10-04T17:07:05'), (u'bibcode', u'2002JGRA..107.1012N'), (u'dates', OrderedDict([(u'date', OrderedDict([(u'@type', u'date-published'), ('#text', u'2002-01-00')]))])), (u'title', u'VHF coherent radar signals from the E region ionosphere and the relationship to electron drift velocity and ion acoustic velocity'), (u'abstract', u'The Scandinavian Twin Auroral Radar Experiment (STARE) coherent radar system measures the Doppler shifts caused by ~1 m plasma waves in the high-latitude E region ionosphere. These Doppler velocities are here related to the electron drift velocity and ion acoustic velocity derived from measurements with the incoherent radar system European Incoherent Scatter (EISCAT). The Doppler velocity is limited in magnitude to near the ion acoustic velocity in the plasma. For large flow angles \u03b8, i.e., the angle between the radar line of sight and the electron drift velocity, the Doppler shifts are equal to the component of the electron drift velocity on the line of sight. For \u03b8 ~ 40\xb0 the Doppler velocity is equal to the ion acoustic velocity at 105-km altitude, and for decreasing flow angle the Doppler velocity increases. For 0\xb0 < \u03b8 < 60\xb0 the variation with flow angle can be described as cos<SUP>\u03b1</SUP>\u03b8, where the \u03b1 decreases from 0.8 to 0.2 with an increase in drift speed from ~400 to 1600 ms<SUP>-1</SUP>. The ratio of the line-of-sight velocity for \u03b8 ~ 0\xb0 to the ion acoustic velocity decreases from 1.2 at low velocities to 1.05 at large velocities. The systematic variations of the Doppler shifts with drift speed and flow angle make it possible, in principle, to recover the electron velocity from the coherent radar measurements. The observations are used to illustrate how well the recovery is possible in practice.'), (u'author', [OrderedDict([(u'@nr', u'1'), (u'name', OrderedDict([(u'western', u'Nielsen, E.'), (u'normalized', u'Nielsen, E')])), (u'type', u'regular')]), OrderedDict([(u'@nr', u'2'), (u'name', OrderedDict([(u'western', u'del Pozo, C. OrderedDict([(u'date', OrderedDict([(u'@type', u'date-preprint'), ('#text', u'2010-02-00')]))])), (u'title', u'The Spectrum of the Isotropic Diffuse Gamma-Ray Emission Derived From First-Year Fermi Large Area Telescope Data'), (u'abstract', u'We report on the first Fermi Large Area Telescope (LAT) measurements of the so-called "extra-galactic" diffuse gamma-ray emission (EGB). This component of the diffuse gamma-ray emission is generally considered to have an isotropic or nearly isotropic distribution on the sky with diverse contributions discussed in the literature. The derivation of the EGB is based on detailed modelling of the bright foreground diffuse Galactic gamma-ray emission (DGE), the detected LAT sources and the solar gamma-ray emission. We find the spectrum of the EGB is consistent with a power law with differential spectral index g = 2.41+/-0.05 and intensity, I(> 100 MeV) = (1.03+/-0.17) 10^-5 cm^-2 s^-1 sr^-1, where the error is systematics dominated. Our EGB spectrum is featureless, less intense, and softer than that derived from EGRET data.'), (u'author', OrderedDict([(u'@nr', u'1'), (u'name', OrderedDict([(u'western', u'The Fermi-LAT collaboration'), (u'normalized', u'The Fermi-LAT collaboration')])), (u'type', u'regular')])), (u'journal', u'eprint arXiv:1002.3603'), (u'page_range', u'3603'), (u'canonical_journal', u'ArXiv e-prints'), (u'publication_year', u'2010'), (u'page', u'3603'), (u'arxivcategories', OrderedDict([(u'arxivcategory', [OrderedDict([(u'@type', u'main'), ('#text', u'Astrophysics - High Energy Astrophysical Phenomena')]), u'Astrophysics - Cosmology and Extragalactic Astrophysics'])])), (u'keywords', OrderedDict([(u'@type', u'arXiv'), (u'keyword', [OrderedDict([(u'@channel', u'astro-ph.HE'), (u'original', u'Astrophysics - High Energy Astrophysical Phenomena'), (u'normalized', None)]), OrderedDict([(u'@channel', u'astro-ph.CO'), (u'original', u'Astrophysics - Cosmology and Extragalactic Astrophysics'), (u'normalized', None)])])])), (u'comment', OrderedDict([(u'@origin', u'ADS'), ('#text', u'4 figures, 1 table, supplementary material, accepted by Physical Review Letters; A MKID is an energy sensor based on a photon-variable superconducting inductance in a lithographed microresonator, and is capable of functioning as a photon detector across the electromagnetic spectrum as well as a particle detector. Here we describe the first successful effort to create a photon-counting, energy-resolving ultraviolet, optical, and near infrared MKID focal plane array. These new Optical Lumped Element (OLE) MKID arrays have significant advantages over semiconductor detectors like charge coupled devices (CCDs). They can count individual photons with essentially no false counts and determine the energy and arrival time of every photon with good quantum efficiency. Their physical pixel size and maximum count rate is well matched with large telescopes. These capabilities enable powerful new astrophysical instruments usable from the ground and space. MKIDs could eventually supplant semiconductor detectors for most astronomical instrumentation, and will be useful for other disciplines such as quantum optics and biological imaging.'), (u'author', [OrderedDict([(u'@nr', u'1'), (u'name', OrderedDict([(u'western', u'Mazin, Benjamin A.'), (u'normalized', u'Mazin, B')])), (u'type', u'regular')]), OrderedDict([(u'@nr', u'2'), (u'name', OrderedDict([(u'western', u'Bumble, Bruce'), (u'normalized', u'Bumble, B')])), (u'type', u'regular')]), OrderedDict([(u'@nr', u'3'), (u'name', OrderedDict([(u'western', u'Meeker, Seth R.'), (u'normalized', u'Meeker, S')])), (u'type', u'regular')]), OrderedDict([(u'@nr', u'4'), (u'name', OrderedDict([(u'western', u"O'Brien, Kieran"), (u'normalized', u"O'Brien, K")])), (u'type', u'regular')]), OrderedDict([(u'@nr', u'5'), (u'name', OrderedDict([(u'western', u'McHugh, Sean'), (u'normalized', u'McHugh, S')])), (u'type', u'regular')]), OrderedDict([(u'@nr', u'6'), (u'name', OrderedDict([(u'western', u'Langman, Eric'), (u'normalized', u'Langman, E')])), (u'type', u'regular')])]), (u'journal', u'eprint arXiv:1112.0004'), (u'page_range', u'4'), (u'canonical_journal', u'ArXiv e-prints'), (u'publication_year', u'2011'), (u'page', u'4'), (u'arxivcategories', OrderedDict([(u'arxivcategory', [OrderedDict([(u'@type', u'main'), ('#text', u'Astrophysics - Instrumentation and Methods for Astrophysics')]), u'Condensed Matter - Superconductivity'])])), (u'keywords', OrderedDict([(u'@type', u'arXiv'), (u'keyword', [OrderedDict([(u'@channel', u'astro-ph.IM'), (u'original', u'Astrophysics - Instrumentation and Methods for Astrophysics'), (u'normalized', None)]), OrderedDict([(u'@channel', u'cond-mat.supr-con'), (u'original', u'Condensed Matter - Superconductivity'), (u'normalized', None)])])])), (u'comment', OrderedDict([(u'@origin', u'ADS'), ('#text', u'9 pages, 5 figures, accepted for publication in Optics Express; The fraction is found to be higher in H2 than had been predicted by Bussard, Ramaty, and Drachman (1979). OrderedDict([(u'@bibcode', u'2014ApJ...784L..17L'), (u'metadata', [OrderedDict([(u'@origin', u'IOP'), (u'@type', u'general'), (u'@primary', u'True'), (u'@alternate_journal', u'False'), (u'creation_time', u'2014-05-15T17:43:22'), (u'modification_time', u'2014-05-15T17:43:22'), (u'bibcode', u'2014ApJ...784L..17L'), (u'dates', OrderedDict([(u'date', OrderedDict([(u'@type', u'date-published'), ('#text', u'2014-03-00')]))])), (u'title', u'The Effect of Isotopic Splitting on the Bisector and Inversions of the Solar Ca II 854.2 nm Line'), (u'abstract', u'The Ca II 854.2 nm spectral line is a common diagnostic of the solar chromosphere. The average line profile shows an asymmetric core, and its bisector shows a characteristic inverse-C shape. The line actually consists of six components with slightly different wavelengths depending on the isotope of calcium. This isotopic splitting of the line has been taken into account in studies of non-solar stars, but never for the Sun. We performed non-LTE radiative transfer computations from three models of the solar atmosphere and show that the line-core asymmetry and inverse C-shape of the bisector of the 854.2 nm line can be explained by isotopic splitting. We confirm this finding by analyzing observations and showing that the line asymmetry is present irrespective of conditions in the solar atmosphere. Finally, we show that inversions based on the Ca II 854.2 nm line should take the isotopic splitting into account, otherwise the inferred atmospheres will contain erroneous velocity gradients and temperatures.'), (u'author', [OrderedDict([(u'@nr', u'1'), (u'name', OrderedDict([(u'western', u'Leenaarts, Jorrit'), (u'normalized', u'Leenaarts, J')])), (u'affiliations', OrderedDict([(u'affiliation', u'Institute of Theoretical Astrophysics, University of Oslo, P.O. The average line profile shows an asymmetric core, and its bisector shows a characteristic inverse-C shape. The line actually consists of six components with slightly different wavelengths depending on the isotope of calcium. This isotopic splitting of the line has been taken into account in studies of non-solar stars, but never for the Sun. We performed non-LTE radiative transfer computations from three models of the solar atmosphere and show that the asymmetric line-core and inverse C-shape of the bisector of the 854.2 nm line can be explained by isotopic splitting. We confirm this finding by analysing observations and showing that the line asymmetry is present irrespective of conditions in the solar atmosphere. Finally, we show that inversions based on the Ca II 854.2 nm line should take the isotopic splitting into account, otherwise the inferred atmospheres will contain erroneous velocity gradients and temperatures.'), (u'author', [OrderedDict([(u'@nr', u'1'), (u'name', OrderedDict([(u'western', u'Leenaarts, Jorrit'), (u'normalized', u'Leenaarts, J')])), (u'type', u'regular')]), OrderedDict([(u'@nr', u'2'), (u'name', OrderedDict([(u'western', u'de la Cruz Rodr\xedguez, Jaime'), (u'normalized', u'de la Cruz Rodriguez, J')])), (u'type', u'regular')]), OrderedDict([(u'@nr', u'3'), (u'name', OrderedDict([(u'western', u'Kochukhov, Oleg'), (u'normalized', u'Kochukhov, O')])), (u'type', u'regular')]), OrderedDict([(u'@nr', u'4'), (u'name', OrderedDict([(u'western', u'Carlsson, Mats'), (u'normalized', u'Carlsson, M')])), (u'type', u'regular')])]), (u'journal', u'eprint arXiv:1401.5019'), (u'page_range', u'5019'), (u'canonical_journal', u'ArXiv e-prints'), (u'publication_year', u'2014'), (u'page', u'5019'), (u'arxivcategories', OrderedDict([(u'arxivcategory', OrderedDict([(u'@type', u'main'), ('#text', u'Astrophysics - OrderedDict([(u'@bibcode', u'2013ApJ...778...51K'), (u'metadata', [OrderedDict([(u'@origin', u'IOP'), (u'@type', u'general'), (u'@primary', u'True'), (u'@alternate_journal', u'False'), (u'creation_time', u'2013-11-07T18:04:54'), (u'modification_time', u'2013-11-07T18:04:54'), (u'bibcode', u'2013ApJ...778...51K'), (u'dates', OrderedDict([(u'date', OrderedDict([(u'@type', u'date-published'), ('#text', u'2013-11-00')]))])), (u'title', u'Investigating the Presence of 500 \u03bcm Submillimeter Excess Emission in Local Star Forming Galaxies'), (u'abstract', u'Submillimeter excess emission has been reported at 500 \u03bcm in a handful of local galaxies, and previous studies suggest that it could be correlated with metal abundance. We investigate the presence of an excess submillimeter emission at 500 \u03bcm for a sample of 20 galaxies from the Key Insights on Nearby Galaxies: a Far Infrared Survey with Herschel (KINGFISH) that span a range of morphologies and metallicities (12 + log (O/H) = 7.8-8.7). We probe the far-infrared (IR) emission using images from the Spitzer Space Telescope and Herschel Space Observatory in the wavelength range 24-500 \u03bcm. We model the far-IR peak of the dust emission with a two-temperature modified blackbody and measure excess of the 500 \u03bcm photometry relative to that predicted by our model. We compare the submillimeter excess, where present, with global galaxy metallicity and, where available, resolved metallicity measurements. We do not find any correlation between the 500 \u03bcm excess and metallicity. A few individual sources do show excess (10%-20%) at 500 \u03bcm conversely, for other sources, the model overpredicts the measured 500 \u03bcm flux density by as much as 20%, creating a 500 \u03bcm "deficit." None of our sources has an excess larger than the calculated 1\u03c3 uncertainty, leading us to conclude that there is no substantial excess at submillimeter wavelengths at or shorter than 500 \u03bcm in our sample. Our results differ from previous studies detecting 500 \u03bcm excess in KINGFISH galaxies largely due to new, improved photometry used in this study.'), (u'author', [OrderedDict([(u'@nr', u'1'), OrderedDict([(u'@type', u'date-preprint'), ('#text', u'2013-10-00')]))])), (u'title', u'Investigating the presence of 500 um submillimeter excess emission in local star forming galaxies'), (u'abstract', u'Submillimeter excess emission has been reported at 500 microns in a handful of local galaxies, and previous studies suggest that it could be correlated with metal abundance. We investigate the presence of an excess submillimeter emission at 500 microns for a sample of 20 galaxies from the Key Insights on Nearby Galaxies: a Far Infrared Survey with Herschel (KINGFISH) that span a range of morphologies and metallicities (12+log(O/H)=7.8-8.7). We probe the far-infrared (IR) emission using images from the Spitzer Space Telescope and Herschel Space Observatory in the wavelength range 24-500 microns. We model the far-IR peak of the dust emission with a two-temperature modified blackbody and measure excess of the 500 micron photometry relative to that predicted by our model. We compare the submillimeter excess, where present, with global galaxy metallicity and, where available, resolved metallicity measurements. We do not find any correlation between the 500 micron excess and metallicity. A few individual sources do show excess (10-20%) at 500 microns; conversely, for other sources, the model overpredicts the measured 500 micron flux density by as much as 20%, creating a 500 micron "deficit". None of our sources has an excess larger than the calculated 1-sigma uncertainty, leading us to conclude that there is no substantial excess at submillimeter wavelengths at or shorter than 500 microns in our sample. Our results differ from previous studies detecting 500 micron excess in KINGFISH galaxies largely due to new, improved photometry used in this study.'), (u'author', [OrderedDict([(u'@nr', u'1'), OrderedDict([(u'@bibcode', u'2002JGRA..107.1012N'), (u'metadata', [OrderedDict([(u'@origin', u'AGU'), (u'@type', u'general'), (u'@primary', u'True'), (u'@alternate_journal', u'False'), (u'creation_time', u'2011-10-04T17:07:05'), (u'modification_time', u'2011-10-04T17:07:05'), (u'bibcode', u'2002JGRA..107.1012N'), (u'dates', OrderedDict([(u'date', OrderedDict([(u'@type', u'date-published'), ('#text', u'2002-01-00')]))])), (u'title', u'VHF coherent radar signals from the E region ionosphere and the relationship to electron drift velocity and ion acoustic velocity'), (u'abstract', u'The Scandinavian Twin Auroral Radar Experiment (STARE) coherent radar system measures the Doppler shifts caused by ~1 m plasma waves in the high-latitude E region ionosphere. These Doppler velocities are here related to the electron drift velocity and ion acoustic velocity derived from measurements with the incoherent radar system European Incoherent Scatter (EISCAT). The Doppler velocity is limited in magnitude to near the ion acoustic velocity in the plasma. For large flow angles \u03b8, i.e., the angle between the radar line of sight and the electron drift velocity, the Doppler shifts are equal to the component of the electron drift velocity on the line of sight. For \u03b8 ~ 40\xb0 the Doppler velocity is equal to the ion acoustic velocity at 105-km altitude, and for decreasing flow angle the Doppler velocity increases. For 0\xb0 < \u03b8 < 60\xb0 the variation with flow angle can be described as cos<SUP>\u03b1</SUP>\u03b8, where the \u03b1 decreases from 0.8 to 0.2 with an increase in drift speed from ~400 to 1600 ms<SUP>-1</SUP>. The ratio of the line-of-sight velocity for \u03b8 ~ 0\xb0 to the ion acoustic velocity decreases from 1.2 at low velocities to 1.05 at large velocities. The systematic variations of the Doppler shifts with drift speed and flow angle make it possible, in principle, to recover the electron velocity from the coherent radar measurements. The observations are used to illustrate how well the recovery is possible in practice.'), (u'author', [OrderedDict([(u'@nr', u'1'), (u'name', OrderedDict([(u'western', u'Nielsen, E.'), (u'normalized', u'Nielsen, E')])), (u'type', u'regular')]), OrderedDict([(u'@nr', u'2'), (u'name', OrderedDict([(u'western', u'del Pozo, C. A MKID is an energy sensor based on a photon-variable superconducting inductance in a lithographed microresonator, and is capable of functioning as a photon detector across the electromagnetic spectrum as well as a particle detector. Here we describe the first successful effort to create a photon-counting, energy-resolving ultraviolet, optical, and near infrared MKID focal plane array. These new Optical Lumped Element (OLE) MKID arrays have significant advantages over semiconductor detectors like charge coupled devices (CCDs). They can count individual photons with essentially no false counts and determine the energy and arrival time of every photon with good quantum efficiency. Their physical pixel size and maximum count rate is well matched with large telescopes. These capabilities enable powerful new astrophysical instruments usable from the ground and space. MKIDs could eventually supplant semiconductor detectors for most astronomical instrumentation, and will be useful for other disciplines such as quantum optics and biological imaging.'), (u'author', [OrderedDict([(u'@nr', u'1'), (u'name', OrderedDict([(u'western', u'Mazin, Benjamin A.'), (u'normalized', u'Mazin, B')])), (u'type', u'regular')]), OrderedDict([(u'@nr', u'2'), (u'name', OrderedDict([(u'western', u'Bumble, Bruce'), (u'normalized', u'Bumble, B')])), (u'type', u'regular')]), OrderedDict([(u'@nr', u'3'), (u'name', OrderedDict([(u'western', u'Meeker, Seth R.'), (u'normalized', u'Meeker, S')])), (u'type', u'regular')]), OrderedDict([(u'@nr', u'4'), (u'name', OrderedDict([(u'western', u"O'Brien, Kieran"), (u'normalized', u"O'Brien, K")])), (u'type', u'regular')]), OrderedDict([(u'@nr', u'5'), (u'name', OrderedDict([(u'western', u'McHugh, Sean'), (u'normalized', u'McHugh, S')])), (u'type', u'regular')]), OrderedDict([(u'@nr', u'6'), (u'name', OrderedDict([(u'western', u'Langman, Eric'), (u'normalized', u'Langman, E')])), (u'type', u'regular')])]), (u'journal', u'eprint arXiv:1112.0004'), (u'page_range', u'4'), (u'canonical_journal', u'ArXiv e-prints'), (u'publication_year', u'2011'), (u'page', u'4'), (u'arxivcategories', OrderedDict([(u'arxivcategory', [OrderedDict([(u'@type', u'main'), ('#text', u'Astrophysics - Instrumentation and Methods for Astrophysics')]), u'Condensed Matter - Superconductivity'])])), (u'keywords', OrderedDict([(u'@type', u'arXiv'), (u'keyword', [OrderedDict([(u'@channel', u'astro-ph.IM'), (u'original', u'Astrophysics - Instrumentation and Methods for Astrophysics'), (u'normalized', None)]), OrderedDict([(u'@channel', u'cond-mat.supr-con'), (u'original', u'Condensed Matter - Superconductivity'), (u'normalized', None)])])])), (u'comment', OrderedDict([(u'@origin', u'ADS'), ('#text', u'9 pages, 5 figures, accepted for publication in Optics Express; Simultaneous observations in other energy bands give us hints about the emission processes during the flare episode and the physics of pulsar wind nebulae in general. <BR /> Aims: We search for variability in the emission of the Crab nebula at very-high energies (VHE; E > 100 GeV), using contemporaneous data taken with the H.E.S.S. array of Cherenkov telescopes. <BR /> Methods: Observational data taken with the H.E.S.S. instrument on five consecutive days during the flare were analysed for the flux and spectral shape of the emission from the Crab nebula. Observations of the Crab during its March 2013 GeV Gamma-Ray Flare'), (u'abstract', u'Context. On March 4, 2013, the Fermi-LAT and AGILE reported a flare from the direction of the Crab Nebula in which the high-energy (HE; E > 100 MeV) flux was six times above its quiescent level. Simultaneous observations in other energy bands give us hints about the emission processes during the flare episode and the physics of pulsar wind nebulae in general. Aims. We search for variability of the emission of the Crab Nebula at very-high energies (VHE; E > 100 GeV), using contemporaneous data taken with the H.E.S.S. array of Cherenkov telescopes. Methods. Observational data taken with the H.E.S.S. instrument on five consecutive days during the flare were analysed concerning the flux and spectral shape of the emission from the Crab Nebula. Night-wise light curves are presented with energy thresholds of 1 TeV and 5 TeV. Results. The observations conducted with H.E.S.S. on 2013 March 6 to March 10 show no significant changes in the flux. They limit the variation on the integral flux above 1 TeV to less than 63% and the integral flux above 5 TeV to less than 78% at a 95% confidence level.'), (u'author', [OrderedDict([(u'@nr', u'1'), (u'name', OrderedDict([(u'western', u'H. A 4 deg full aperture prism, which provides a dispersion of 1950 A/mm, and IIIaF emulsion combination has been used to search for ELGs selected by the presence of H-alpha emission in their spectra. OrderedDict([(u'date', OrderedDict([(u'@type', u'date-preprint'), ('#text', u'2010-02-00')]))])), (u'title', u'The Spectrum of the Isotropic Diffuse Gamma-Ray Emission Derived From First-Year Fermi Large Area Telescope Data'), (u'abstract', u'We report on the first Fermi Large Area Telescope (LAT) measurements of the so-called "extra-galactic" diffuse gamma-ray emission (EGB). This component of the diffuse gamma-ray emission is generally considered to have an isotropic or nearly isotropic distribution on the sky with diverse contributions discussed in the literature. The derivation of the EGB is based on detailed modelling of the bright foreground diffuse Galactic gamma-ray emission (DGE), the detected LAT sources and the solar gamma-ray emission. We find the spectrum of the EGB is consistent with a power law with differential spectral index g = 2.41+/-0.05 and intensity, I(> 100 MeV) = (1.03+/-0.17) 10^-5 cm^-2 s^-1 sr^-1, where the error is systematics dominated. Our EGB spectrum is featureless, less intense, and softer than that derived from EGRET data.'), (u'author', OrderedDict([(u'@nr', u'1'), (u'name', OrderedDict([(u'western', u'The Fermi-LAT collaboration'), (u'normalized', u'The Fermi-LAT collaboration')])), (u'type', u'regular')])), (u'journal', u'eprint arXiv:1002.3603'), (u'page_range', u'3603'), (u'canonical_journal', u'ArXiv e-prints'), (u'publication_year', u'2010'), (u'page', u'3603'), (u'arxivcategories', OrderedDict([(u'arxivcategory', [OrderedDict([(u'@type', u'main'), ('#text', u'Astrophysics - High Energy Astrophysical Phenomena')]), u'Astrophysics - Cosmology and Extragalactic Astrophysics'])])), (u'keywords', OrderedDict([(u'@type', u'arXiv'), (u'keyword', [OrderedDict([(u'@channel', u'astro-ph.HE'), (u'original', u'Astrophysics - High Energy Astrophysical Phenomena'), (u'normalized', None)]), OrderedDict([(u'@channel', u'astro-ph.CO'), (u'original', u'Astrophysics - Cosmology and Extragalactic Astrophysics'), (u'normalized', None)])])])), (u'comment', OrderedDict([(u'@origin', u'ADS'), ('#text', u'4 figures, 1 table, supplementary material, accepted by Physical Review Letters; OrderedDict([(u'@bibcode', u'2002JGRA..107.1012N'), (u'metadata', [OrderedDict([(u'@origin', u'AGU'), (u'@type', u'general'), (u'@primary', u'True'), (u'@alternate_journal', u'False'), (u'creation_time', u'2011-10-04T17:07:05'), (u'modification_time', u'2011-10-04T17:07:05'), (u'bibcode', u'2002JGRA..107.1012N'), (u'dates', OrderedDict([(u'date', OrderedDict([(u'@type', u'date-published'), ('#text', u'2002-01-00')]))])), (u'title', u'VHF coherent radar signals from the E region ionosphere and the relationship to electron drift velocity and ion acoustic velocity'), (u'abstract', u'The Scandinavian Twin Auroral Radar Experiment (STARE) coherent radar system measures the Doppler shifts caused by ~1 m plasma waves in the high-latitude E region ionosphere. These Doppler velocities are here related to the electron drift velocity and ion acoustic velocity derived from measurements with the incoherent radar system European Incoherent Scatter (EISCAT). The Doppler velocity is limited in magnitude to near the ion acoustic velocity in the plasma. For large flow angles \u03b8, i.e., the angle between the radar line of sight and the electron drift velocity, the Doppler shifts are equal to the component of the electron drift velocity on the line of sight. For \u03b8 ~ 40\xb0 the Doppler velocity is equal to the ion acoustic velocity at 105-km altitude, and for decreasing flow angle the Doppler velocity increases. For 0\xb0 < \u03b8 < 60\xb0 the variation with flow angle can be described as cos<SUP>\u03b1</SUP>\u03b8, where the \u03b1 decreases from 0.8 to 0.2 with an increase in drift speed from ~400 to 1600 ms<SUP>-1</SUP>. The ratio of the line-of-sight velocity for \u03b8 ~ 0\xb0 to the ion acoustic velocity decreases from 1.2 at low velocities to 1.05 at large velocities. The systematic variations of the Doppler shifts with drift speed and flow angle make it possible, in principle, to recover the electron velocity from the coherent radar measurements. The observations are used to illustrate how well the recovery is possible in practice.'), (u'author', [OrderedDict([(u'@nr', u'1'), (u'name', OrderedDict([(u'western', u'Nielsen, E.'), (u'normalized', u'Nielsen, E')])), (u'type', u'regular')]), OrderedDict([(u'@nr', u'2'), (u'name', OrderedDict([(u'western', u'del Pozo, C. OrderedDict([(u'@bibcode', u'2005AcSpe..60.1230K'), (u'metadata', [OrderedDict([(u'@origin', u'ELSEVIER'), (u'@type', u'general'), (u'@primary', u'True'), (u'@alternate_journal', u'False'), (u'creation_time', u'2013-10-16T18:04:01'), (u'modification_time', u'2013-10-16T18:04:01'), (u'bibcode', u'2005AcSpe..60.1230K'), (u'dates', OrderedDict([(u'date', OrderedDict([(u'@type', u'date-published'), ('#text', u'2005-08-00')]))])), (u'title', u'Detection of manganese in solution in cavitation bubbles using laser induced breakdown spectroscopy'), (u'abstract', u'Levels of dissolved manganese in water samples down to 80 \u03bcg/l are measured using emission spectroscopy. Optical emission spectroscopic methods tend to be insensitive in liquids due to strong quenching processes. Laser induced breakdown spectroscopy (LIBS) within a cavitation bubble overcomes this restriction. The output of a double pulsed Q-switched Nd:YAG laser, operated at 532 nm, is coupled to an optical fibre. The fibre guides the laser pulses to a silicon target immersed in a water sample contaminated with manganese. The cavitation process is initiated with the first laser pulse. At maximum bubble expansion, the second laser pulse ignites the plasma in the vapour/gas-filled cavitation bubble. Emission is collected by an additional optical fibre located near the bubble. Characteristic spectral line intensities of manganese are recorded and correlated to an internal calibration standard. Spectral analysis and data acquisition are carried out using an image-intensified optical multi-channel analyser.'), (u'author', [OrderedDict([(u'@nr', u'1'), (u'name', OrderedDict([(u'western', A MKID is an energy sensor based on a photon-variable superconducting inductance in a lithographed microresonator, and is capable of functioning as a photon detector across the electromagnetic spectrum as well as a particle detector. Here we describe the first successful effort to create a photon-counting, energy-resolving ultraviolet, optical, and near infrared MKID focal plane array. These new Optical Lumped Element (OLE) MKID arrays have significant advantages over semiconductor detectors like charge coupled devices (CCDs). They can count individual photons with essentially no false counts and determine the energy and arrival time of every photon with good quantum efficiency. Their physical pixel size and maximum count rate is well matched with large telescopes. These capabilities enable powerful new astrophysical instruments usable from the ground and space. MKIDs could eventually supplant semiconductor detectors for most astronomical instrumentation, and will be useful for other disciplines such as quantum optics and biological imaging.'), (u'author', [OrderedDict([(u'@nr', u'1'), (u'name', OrderedDict([(u'western', u'Mazin, Benjamin A.'), (u'normalized', u'Mazin, B')])), (u'type', u'regular')]), OrderedDict([(u'@nr', u'2'), (u'name', OrderedDict([(u'western', u'Bumble, Bruce'), (u'normalized', u'Bumble, B')])), (u'type', u'regular')]), OrderedDict([(u'@nr', u'3'), (u'name', OrderedDict([(u'western', u'Meeker, Seth R.'), (u'normalized', u'Meeker, S')])), (u'type', u'regular')]), OrderedDict([(u'@nr', u'4'), (u'name', OrderedDict([(u'western', u"O'Brien, Kieran"), (u'normalized', u"O'Brien, K")])), (u'type', u'regular')]), OrderedDict([(u'@nr', u'5'), (u'name', OrderedDict([(u'western', u'McHugh, Sean'), (u'normalized', u'McHugh, S')])), (u'type', u'regular')]), OrderedDict([(u'@nr', u'6'), (u'name', OrderedDict([(u'western', u'Langman, Eric'), (u'normalized', u'Langman, E')])), (u'type', u'regular')])]), (u'journal', u'eprint arXiv:1112.0004'), (u'page_range', u'4'), (u'canonical_journal', u'ArXiv e-prints'), (u'publication_year', u'2011'), (u'page', u'4'), (u'arxivcategories', OrderedDict([(u'arxivcategory', [OrderedDict([(u'@type', u'main'), ('#text', u'Astrophysics - Instrumentation and Methods for Astrophysics')]), u'Condensed Matter - Superconductivity'])])), (u'keywords', OrderedDict([(u'@type', u'arXiv'), (u'keyword', [OrderedDict([(u'@channel', u'astro-ph.IM'), (u'original', u'Astrophysics - Instrumentation and Methods for Astrophysics'), (u'normalized', None)]), OrderedDict([(u'@channel', u'cond-mat.supr-con'), (u'original', u'Condensed Matter - Superconductivity'), (u'normalized', None)])])])), (u'comment', OrderedDict([(u'@origin', u'ADS'), ('#text', u'9 pages, 5 figures, accepted for publication in Optics Express; OrderedDict([(u'date', OrderedDict([(u'@type', u'date-preprint'), ('#text', u'2010-02-00')]))])), (u'title', u'The Spectrum of the Isotropic Diffuse Gamma-Ray Emission Derived From First-Year Fermi Large Area Telescope Data'), (u'abstract', u'We report on the first Fermi Large Area Telescope (LAT) measurements of the so-called "extra-galactic" diffuse gamma-ray emission (EGB). This component of the diffuse gamma-ray emission is generally considered to have an isotropic or nearly isotropic distribution on the sky with diverse contributions discussed in the literature. The derivation of the EGB is based on detailed modelling of the bright foreground diffuse Galactic gamma-ray emission (DGE), the detected LAT sources and the solar gamma-ray emission. We find the spectrum of the EGB is consistent with a power law with differential spectral index g = 2.41+/-0.05 and intensity, I(> 100 MeV) = (1.03+/-0.17) 10^-5 cm^-2 s^-1 sr^-1, where the error is systematics dominated. Our EGB spectrum is featureless, less intense, and softer than that derived from EGRET data.'), (u'author', OrderedDict([(u'@nr', u'1'), (u'name', OrderedDict([(u'western', u'The Fermi-LAT collaboration'), (u'normalized', u'The Fermi-LAT collaboration')])), (u'type', u'regular')])), (u'journal', u'eprint arXiv:1002.3603'), (u'page_range', u'3603'), (u'canonical_journal', u'ArXiv e-prints'), (u'publication_year', u'2010'), (u'page', u'3603'), (u'arxivcategories', OrderedDict([(u'arxivcategory', [OrderedDict([(u'@type', u'main'), ('#text', u'Astrophysics - High Energy Astrophysical Phenomena')]), u'Astrophysics - Cosmology and Extragalactic Astrophysics'])])), (u'keywords', OrderedDict([(u'@type', u'arXiv'), (u'keyword', [OrderedDict([(u'@channel', u'astro-ph.HE'), (u'original', u'Astrophysics - High Energy Astrophysical Phenomena'), (u'normalized', None)]), OrderedDict([(u'@channel', u'astro-ph.CO'), (u'original', u'Astrophysics - Cosmology and Extragalactic Astrophysics'), (u'normalized', None)])])])), (u'comment', OrderedDict([(u'@origin', u'ADS'), ('#text', u'4 figures, 1 table, supplementary material, accepted by Physical Review Letters; III - NGC 3998'), (u'abstract', u'Synthesis observations of H I in the active S0 galaxy NGC 3998 show that the gas is in a polar ring, inclined about 80\xb0 to the optical major axis. The position angle of the ionized gas in the inner galaxy is intermediate between those of H I and the light, suggesting differential precession of the gas structure. Weak extensions on the radio continuum emission from the nucleus are roughly perpendicular to the inner gas distribution. The circular velocity derived from the H I is normal for a galaxy of this luminosity; however, the ratio of central bulge velocity dispersion to circular velocity is anomalously high. This, and the extreme central light concentration, suggest that the galaxy contains a central massive object.'), (u'author', [OrderedDict([(u'@nr', u'1'), (u'name', OrderedDict([(u'western', u'Knapp, G. Axisymmetric models are considered and compared with stellar photometric data; in addition, the theoretical spiral pattern of the stellar wave computed on the basis of linear stellar density-wave theory is discussed. Further, gasdynamical models for M 81 are presented and compared with high-resolution H-line observations. OrderedDict([(u'@bibcode', u'2002JGRA..107.1012N'), (u'metadata', [OrderedDict([(u'@origin', u'AGU'), (u'@type', u'general'), (u'@primary', u'True'), (u'@alternate_journal', u'False'), (u'creation_time', u'2011-10-04T17:07:05'), (u'modification_time', u'2011-10-04T17:07:05'), (u'bibcode', u'2002JGRA..107.1012N'), (u'dates', OrderedDict([(u'date', OrderedDict([(u'@type', u'date-published'), ('#text', u'2002-01-00')]))])), (u'title', u'VHF coherent radar signals from the E region ionosphere and the relationship to electron drift velocity and ion acoustic velocity'), (u'abstract', u'The Scandinavian Twin Auroral Radar Experiment (STARE) coherent radar system measures the Doppler shifts caused by ~1 m plasma waves in the high-latitude E region ionosphere. These Doppler velocities are here related to the electron drift velocity and ion acoustic velocity derived from measurements with the incoherent radar system European Incoherent Scatter (EISCAT). The Doppler velocity is limited in magnitude to near the ion acoustic velocity in the plasma. For large flow angles \u03b8, i.e., the angle between the radar line of sight and the electron drift velocity, the Doppler shifts are equal to the component of the electron drift velocity on the line of sight. For \u03b8 ~ 40\xb0 the Doppler velocity is equal to the ion acoustic velocity at 105-km altitude, and for decreasing flow angle the Doppler velocity increases. For 0\xb0 < \u03b8 < 60\xb0 the variation with flow angle can be described as cos<SUP>\u03b1</SUP>\u03b8, where the \u03b1 decreases from 0.8 to 0.2 with an increase in drift speed from ~400 to 1600 ms<SUP>-1</SUP>. The ratio of the line-of-sight velocity for \u03b8 ~ 0\xb0 to the ion acoustic velocity decreases from 1.2 at low velocities to 1.05 at large velocities. The systematic variations of the Doppler shifts with drift speed and flow angle make it possible, in principle, to recover the electron velocity from the coherent radar measurements. The observations are used to illustrate how well the recovery is possible in practice.'), (u'author', [OrderedDict([(u'@nr', u'1'), (u'name', OrderedDict([(u'western', u'Nielsen, E.'), (u'normalized', u'Nielsen, E')])), (u'type', u'regular')]), OrderedDict([(u'@nr', u'2'), (u'name', OrderedDict([(u'western', u'del Pozo, C. Extragalactic distances, Hubble constant and the age of the Universe. Part II. The long and short distance scales - comparison of two approaches to the Hubble constant. Part III. Five crucial tests of the extragalactic distance scale using the Galaxy as fundamental calibrator: 1. Introduction. 2. The Galaxy as fundamental calibrator. 3. The basic metric and photometric scale factors of the Galaxy. 4. Galactic zero points of the B- and H-band Tully-Fisher relations and a first test of the long and short distance scales. 5. Galactic zero points of the B- and V-band Faber-Jackson relations and a second test of the long and short distance scales. 6. Third test: metric and photometric scale lengths in the Galaxy and galactic zero points for the luminosity index scale. 7. Absorption features reveal that this system is at a redshift of $z=2.72$, implying an absolute magnitude of ${\\rm M_v \\sim -26}$, and a star-formation rate of $4700 {\\rm M_{\\odot} yr^{-1}}$, making it the most ``active'' star-forming galaxy. This proto-galaxy is observed to lie close $\\left(\\sim 6\\scnp\\right)$ to a central cluster galaxy at $z=0.373$. The X-ray properties of the cluster suggest that its mass, and therefore its lensing potential, could be greater than that found using a virial analysis. OrderedDict([(u'@bibcode', u'2014ApJ...784L..17L'), (u'metadata', [OrderedDict([(u'@origin', u'IOP'), (u'@type', u'general'), (u'@primary', u'True'), (u'@alternate_journal', u'False'), (u'creation_time', u'2014-05-15T17:43:22'), (u'modification_time', u'2014-05-15T17:43:22'), (u'bibcode', u'2014ApJ...784L..17L'), (u'dates', OrderedDict([(u'date', OrderedDict([(u'@type', u'date-published'), ('#text', u'2014-03-00')]))])), (u'title', u'The Effect of Isotopic Splitting on the Bisector and Inversions of the Solar Ca II 854.2 nm Line'), (u'abstract', u'The Ca II 854.2 nm spectral line is a common diagnostic of the solar chromosphere. The average line profile shows an asymmetric core, and its bisector shows a characteristic inverse-C shape. The line actually consists of six components with slightly different wavelengths depending on the isotope of calcium. This isotopic splitting of the line has been taken into account in studies of non-solar stars, but never for the Sun. We performed non-LTE radiative transfer computations from three models of the solar atmosphere and show that the line-core asymmetry and inverse C-shape of the bisector of the 854.2 nm line can be explained by isotopic splitting. We confirm this finding by analyzing observations and showing that the line asymmetry is present irrespective of conditions in the solar atmosphere. Finally, we show that inversions based on the Ca II 854.2 nm line should take the isotopic splitting into account, otherwise the inferred atmospheres will contain erroneous velocity gradients and temperatures.'), (u'author', [OrderedDict([(u'@nr', u'1'), (u'name', OrderedDict([(u'western', u'Leenaarts, Jorrit'), (u'normalized', u'Leenaarts, J')])), (u'affiliations', OrderedDict([(u'affiliation', u'Institute of Theoretical Astrophysics, University of Oslo, P.O. The average line profile shows an asymmetric core, and its bisector shows a characteristic inverse-C shape. The line actually consists of six components with slightly different wavelengths depending on the isotope of calcium. This isotopic splitting of the line has been taken into account in studies of non-solar stars, but never for the Sun. We performed non-LTE radiative transfer computations from three models of the solar atmosphere and show that the asymmetric line-core and inverse C-shape of the bisector of the 854.2 nm line can be explained by isotopic splitting. We confirm this finding by analysing observations and showing that the line asymmetry is present irrespective of conditions in the solar atmosphere. Finally, we show that inversions based on the Ca II 854.2 nm line should take the isotopic splitting into account, otherwise the inferred atmospheres will contain erroneous velocity gradients and temperatures.'), (u'author', [OrderedDict([(u'@nr', u'1'), (u'name', OrderedDict([(u'western', u'Leenaarts, Jorrit'), (u'normalized', u'Leenaarts, J')])), (u'type', u'regular')]), OrderedDict([(u'@nr', u'2'), (u'name', OrderedDict([(u'western', u'de la Cruz Rodr\xedguez, Jaime'), (u'normalized', u'de la Cruz Rodriguez, J')])), (u'type', u'regular')]), OrderedDict([(u'@nr', u'3'), (u'name', OrderedDict([(u'western', u'Kochukhov, Oleg'), (u'normalized', u'Kochukhov, O')])), (u'type', u'regular')]), OrderedDict([(u'@nr', u'4'), (u'name', OrderedDict([(u'western', u'Carlsson, Mats'), (u'normalized', u'Carlsson, M')])), (u'type', u'regular')])]), (u'journal', u'eprint arXiv:1401.5019'), (u'page_range', u'5019'), (u'canonical_journal', u'ArXiv e-prints'), (u'publication_year', u'2014'), (u'page', u'5019'), (u'arxivcategories', OrderedDict([(u'arxivcategory', OrderedDict([(u'@type', u'main'), ('#text', u'Astrophysics - OrderedDict([(u'@bibcode', u'1986PhDT.........1A'), (u'metadata', [OrderedDict([(u'@origin', u'UMI'), (u'@type', u'general'), (u'@primary', u'False'), (u'@alternate_journal', u'False'), (u'creation_time', u'2012-07-12T13:52:42'), (u'modification_time', u'2012-07-12T13:52:42'), (u'bibcode', u'1986PhDT.........1A'), (u'dates', OrderedDict([(u'date', OrderedDict([(u'@type', u'date-thesis'), ('#text', u'1986-00-00')]))])), (u'title', u'Problems in Quantum Cosmology.'), (u'abstract', u'The standard cosmological model is reviewed and shown not to be self-sufficient in that it requires initial conditions which are most likely to be supplied by quantum cosmology. The possible approaches to the issue of initial conditions for cosmology are then discussed. In this thesis, I shall consider three separate problems related to this issue. First, the possibility of inflation is investigated in detail by analyzing the evolution of metric perturbations and fluctuations in the expectation value of a scalar field prior to a phase transition; finite temperature effects are also included. Since the inhomogeneities were damped well before the onset of a phase transition, I conclude that an inflation was possible. Next, the effective action of neutrino and photon fields is calculated for homogeneous spacetimes with small anisotropy, and is shown that quantum corrections to the action due to these fields influence the evolution of an early Universe in the same way as do the analogous correction terms arising from a conformally invariant scalar which has been previously studied. I thus conclude that the physical processes of neutrino and photon production could rapidly dissipate any anisotropy in an early Universe. In addition, I have extended the scalar field calculations to finite temperature, where it is shown that the probability of the particle production is enhanced. Contrary to the T = 0 case, though, finite temperature necessitates the consideration of the nonlocal term in the action. Finally, the question of an early anisotropy is also discussed in a framework of Hartle-Hawking "wave function of the Universe". A wave function of a Bianchi IX type Universe is calculated in a semiclassical approximation for a model with a cosmological constant, and by solving the Wheeler-DeWitt equation numerically for a model with classical radiation. It is shown that an anisotropic Universe is very unlikely, and that the expectation value of the anisotropy energy density decreases very fast as the Universe expands.'), (u'author', OrderedDict([(u'@nr', u'1'), (u'name', OrderedDict([(u'western', u'Amsterdamski, Piotr'), (u'normalized', u'Amsterdamski, P')])), (u'affiliations', OrderedDict([(u'affiliation', u'UNIVERSITY OF CALIFORNIA, SANTA BARBARA.')])), (u'type', u'regular')])), (u'ADSaffiliation', u'AA(UNIVERSITY OF CALIFORNIA, SANTA BARBARA.)'), (u'journal', u'Thesis (PH.D.)--UNIVERSITY OF CALIFORNIA, SANTA BARBARA, 1986.Source: Dissertation Abstracts International,  Volume: 47-09, Section: B, page: 3810.'), (u'canonical_journal', u'Ph.D. Thesis'), (u'publication_year', u'1986'), (u'electronic_id', u's International,  Volume: 47-09, Section: B, page: 3810'), (u'keywords', OrderedDict([(u'@type', u'STI category'), (u'keyword', OrderedDict([(u'@channel', u''), (u'original', u'Physics: Astronomy and Astrophysics'), (u'normalized', None)]))]))]), OrderedDict([(u'@origin', u'STI'), (u'@type', u'general'), (u'@primary', u'True'), (u'@alternate_journal', u'False'), (u'creation_time', u'2013-12-05T03:49:22'), (u'modification_time', u'2013-12-05T03:49:22'), (u'bibcode', u'1986PhDT.........1A'), (u'dates', OrderedDict([(u'date', OrderedDict([(u'@type', u'date-thesis'), ('#text', u'1986-00-00')]))])), (u'title', u'Problems in quantum cosmology'), (u'abstract', u'The standard cosmological model is reviewed and shown not to be self-sufficient in that it requires initial conditions which are most likely to be supplied by quantum cosmology. OrderedDict([(u'@bibcode', u'2010AAS...21542816H'), (u'metadata', [OrderedDict([(u'@origin', u'AAS'), (u'@type', u'general'), (u'@primary', u'True'), (u'@alternate_journal', u'False'), (u'creation_time', u'2012-08-06T19:12:47'), (u'modification_time', u'2012-08-06T19:12:47'), (u'bibcode', u'2010AAS...21542816H'), (u'dates', OrderedDict([(u'date', OrderedDict([(u'@type', u'date-published'), ('#text', u'2010-01-00')]))])), (u'title', u'Characteristics Of Hydrocarbon Emission From Herbig Ae/be Stars'), (u'abstract', u'We present analysis of polycyclic aromatic hydrocarbon (PAH) emission in mid-infrared spectra of a large sample of Herbig Ae and Be (HAeBe) stars. The spectra were obtained with the Infrared Spectrograph on the Spitzer Space Telescope. In a previous study of 18 HAeBe stars we found: evidence that the PAH ionization fraction in the circumstellar material around HAeBe stars is related to the structure of the PAH molecules; that the center wavelengths of the PAH emission features change systematically with stellar effective temperature changes; and that HAeBe stars have may have unique mid-infrared spectral characteristics that distinguish them from other strong PAH emission sources. We also found no simple correlation between the integrated intensity of PAH emission from HAeBe stars and the geometry of their proto-planetary disks. We now have expanded the sample to include 50 stars using archival data from the Spitzer database. We present a similar analysis applied to the larger sample.'), (u'author', [OrderedDict([(u'@nr', u'1'), (u'name', OrderedDict([(u'western', u'Hyatt, Jordan'), (u'normalized', u'Hyatt, J')])), (u'affiliations', OrderedDict([(u'affiliation', u'Ithaca College')])), (u'type', u'regular')]), OrderedDict([(u'@nr', u'2'), (u'name', OrderedDict([(u'western', u'Keller, L. The calculations include a fully general-relativistic treatment of the radiation transfer problem. In both cases general-relativistic corrections can lead to large rotations in the plane of X-ray polarization and to changes in the degree of polarization. Such differences are potentially observable and can be used to distinguish between the two models. The polarization features can indicate whether a black hole is present in a compact X-ray source.'), (u'author', [OrderedDict([(u'@nr', u'1'), (u'name', OrderedDict([(u'western', u'Connors, P. A MKID is an energy sensor based on a photon-variable superconducting inductance in a lithographed microresonator, and is capable of functioning as a photon detector across the electromagnetic spectrum as well as a particle detector. Here we describe the first successful effort to create a photon-counting, energy-resolving ultraviolet, optical, and near infrared MKID focal plane array. These new Optical Lumped Element (OLE) MKID arrays have significant advantages over semiconductor detectors like charge coupled devices (CCDs). They can count individual photons with essentially no false counts and determine the energy and arrival time of every photon with good quantum efficiency. Their physical pixel size and maximum count rate is well matched with large telescopes. These capabilities enable powerful new astrophysical instruments usable from the ground and space. MKIDs could eventually supplant semiconductor detectors for most astronomical instrumentation, and will be useful for other disciplines such as quantum optics and biological imaging.'), (u'author', [OrderedDict([(u'@nr', u'1'), (u'name', OrderedDict([(u'western', u'Mazin, Benjamin A.'), (u'normalized', u'Mazin, B')])), (u'type', u'regular')]), OrderedDict([(u'@nr', u'2'), (u'name', OrderedDict([(u'western', u'Bumble, Bruce'), (u'normalized', u'Bumble, B')])), (u'type', u'regular')]), OrderedDict([(u'@nr', u'3'), (u'name', OrderedDict([(u'western', u'Meeker, Seth R.'), (u'normalized', u'Meeker, S')])), (u'type', u'regular')]), OrderedDict([(u'@nr', u'4'), (u'name', OrderedDict([(u'western', u"O'Brien, Kieran"), (u'normalized', u"O'Brien, K")])), (u'type', u'regular')]), OrderedDict([(u'@nr', u'5'), (u'name', OrderedDict([(u'western', u'McHugh, Sean'), (u'normalized', u'McHugh, S')])), (u'type', u'regular')]), OrderedDict([(u'@nr', u'6'), (u'name', OrderedDict([(u'western', u'Langman, Eric'), (u'normalized', u'Langman, E')])), (u'type', u'regular')])]), (u'journal', u'eprint arXiv:1112.0004'), (u'page_range', u'4'), (u'canonical_journal', u'ArXiv e-prints'), (u'publication_year', u'2011'), (u'page', u'4'), (u'arxivcategories', OrderedDict([(u'arxivcategory', [OrderedDict([(u'@type', u'main'), ('#text', u'Astrophysics - Instrumentation and Methods for Astrophysics')]), u'Condensed Matter - Superconductivity'])])), (u'keywords', OrderedDict([(u'@type', u'arXiv'), (u'keyword', [OrderedDict([(u'@channel', u'astro-ph.IM'), (u'original', u'Astrophysics - Instrumentation and Methods for Astrophysics'), (u'normalized', None)]), OrderedDict([(u'@channel', u'cond-mat.supr-con'), (u'original', u'Condensed Matter - Superconductivity'), (u'normalized', None)])])])), (u'comment', OrderedDict([(u'@origin', u'ADS'), ('#text', u'9 pages, 5 figures, accepted for publication in Optics Express; Radio observations were carried out with the 100-m Robert C. Byrd Green Bank Telescope at the frequency of 8.9 GHz for about of 10.5 h of contemporaneous time with Fermi Space Telescope. These observations are part of the ongoing campaign with two other telescopes, the 140-ft telescope at Green Bank Observatory (WV) and 42-ft telescope at Jodrell Bank Observatory (UK). Using the Bayesian approach we put a conservative limit on average gamma-ray flux increase during GPs to be less than 10 integral fluxes of the Crab pulsar. We investigate the presence of an excess submillimeter emission at 500 \u03bcm for a sample of 20 galaxies from the Key Insights on Nearby Galaxies: a Far Infrared Survey with Herschel (KINGFISH) that span a range of morphologies and metallicities (12 + log (O/H) = 7.8-8.7). We probe the far-infrared (IR) emission using images from the Spitzer Space Telescope and Herschel Space Observatory in the wavelength range 24-500 \u03bcm. We model the far-IR peak of the dust emission with a two-temperature modified blackbody and measure excess of the 500 \u03bcm photometry relative to that predicted by our model. We compare the submillimeter excess, where present, with global galaxy metallicity and, where available, resolved metallicity measurements. We do not find any correlation between the 500 \u03bcm excess and metallicity. A few individual sources do show excess (10%-20%) at 500 \u03bcm conversely, for other sources, the model overpredicts the measured 500 \u03bcm flux density by as much as 20%, creating a 500 \u03bcm "deficit." None of our sources has an excess larger than the calculated 1\u03c3 uncertainty, leading us to conclude that there is no substantial excess at submillimeter wavelengths at or shorter than 500 \u03bcm in our sample. Our results differ from previous studies detecting 500 \u03bcm excess in KINGFISH galaxies largely due to new, improved photometry used in this study.'), (u'author', [OrderedDict([(u'@nr', u'1'), OrderedDict([(u'@type', u'date-preprint'), ('#text', u'2013-10-00')]))])), (u'title', u'Investigating the presence of 500 um submillimeter excess emission in local star forming galaxies'), (u'abstract', u'Submillimeter excess emission has been reported at 500 microns in a handful of local galaxies, and previous studies suggest that it could be correlated with metal abundance. We investigate the presence of an excess submillimeter emission at 500 microns for a sample of 20 galaxies from the Key Insights on Nearby Galaxies: a Far Infrared Survey with Herschel (KINGFISH) that span a range of morphologies and metallicities (12+log(O/H)=7.8-8.7). We probe the far-infrared (IR) emission using images from the Spitzer Space Telescope and Herschel Space Observatory in the wavelength range 24-500 microns. We model the far-IR peak of the dust emission with a two-temperature modified blackbody and measure excess of the 500 micron photometry relative to that predicted by our model. We compare the submillimeter excess, where present, with global galaxy metallicity and, where available, resolved metallicity measurements. We do not find any correlation between the 500 micron excess and metallicity. A few individual sources do show excess (10-20%) at 500 microns; conversely, for other sources, the model overpredicts the measured 500 micron flux density by as much as 20%, creating a 500 micron "deficit". None of our sources has an excess larger than the calculated 1-sigma uncertainty, leading us to conclude that there is no substantial excess at submillimeter wavelengths at or shorter than 500 microns in our sample. Our results differ from previous studies detecting 500 micron excess in KINGFISH galaxies largely due to new, improved photometry used in this study.'), (u'author', [OrderedDict([(u'@nr', u'1'), To be concrete, we have carried out an analysis of the Local Group motion with respect to 10 extragalactic reference frames (concentric shells) constructed from a sample of 300 elliptical galaxies. The results [which confirm the trend found by de Vaucouleurs & Peters (1984) using six shells of galaxies of all types] show that the motion of the shells of galaxies decreases with the distance and that the shell at 30h^-1^ Mpc is at rest in the cosmic microwave background (CMB) frame. Moreover, the results for samples whose mean distance is greater than 30h^-1^ Mpc indicate the possible existence of an inhomogeneity at a distance of ~40h^-1^ Mpc. On the other hand, we can obtain an effective velocity spectrum P_v_(k) proportional to k^-2^, which is valid on scales 5h^-1^- 40h^-1^ Mpc. This spectrum reproduces (as typical values) both the data obtained by de Vaucouleurs & Peters (1984) and the new results derived in this paper. The behaviour proportional to k^-2^ can account for the observations by Hart & Davies (1982) and Aaronson et al. (1982) at 90% confidence level. Moreover, this phenomenological result suggests that the dark matter dominates on scales <~40h^-1^ Mpc (the dynamical behaviour associated with the luminous matter must be characterized by the spectrum P_v_ is proportional to k^-3.2^) We have also established that a universe dominated by adiabatic cold dark matter ({OMEGA} = 1, h = 0.5) is in good agreement with the kinematical data. For these two models [white noise and cold dark matter (CDM)], we discuss the bias parameter compatible with the observational data. Finally, the correlation for Abell clusters (at separations <~ 20h^-1^ Mpc) can be reproduced by means of the models derived from the motions predicted by the kinematical analysis. We have taken the correlation observed by Sutherland (1988) and Sutherland & Efstathiou (1991).'), (u'author', [OrderedDict([(u'@nr', u'1'), (u'name', OrderedDict([(u'western', u'Martin-Mirones, J. On March 4, 2013 the Fermi-LAT and AGILE reported a flare from the direction of the Crab nebula in which the high-energy (HE; E > 100 MeV) flux was six times above its quiescent level. Simultaneous observations in other energy bands give us hints about the emission processes during the flare episode and the physics of pulsar wind nebulae in general. <BR /> Aims: We search for variability in the emission of the Crab nebula at very-high energies (VHE; E > 100 GeV), using contemporaneous data taken with the H.E.S.S. array of Cherenkov telescopes. <BR /> Methods: Observational data taken with the H.E.S.S. instrument on five consecutive days during the flare were analysed for the flux and spectral shape of the emission from the Crab nebula. Night-wise light curves are presented with energy thresholds of 1 TeV and 5 TeV. <BR /> Results: The observations conducted with H.E.S.S. on March 6 to March 10, 2013 show no significant changes in the flux. Observations of the Crab during its March 2013 GeV Gamma-Ray Flare'), (u'abstract', u'Context. On March 4, 2013, the Fermi-LAT and AGILE reported a flare from the direction of the Crab Nebula in which the high-energy (HE; E > 100 MeV) flux was six times above its quiescent level. Simultaneous observations in other energy bands give us hints about the emission processes during the flare episode and the physics of pulsar wind nebulae in general. Aims. We search for variability of the emission of the Crab Nebula at very-high energies (VHE; E > 100 GeV), using contemporaneous data taken with the H.E.S.S. array of Cherenkov telescopes. Methods. Observational data taken with the H.E.S.S. instrument on five consecutive days during the flare were analysed concerning the flux and spectral shape of the emission from the Crab Nebula. Night-wise light curves are presented with energy thresholds of 1 TeV and 5 TeV. Results. The observations conducted with H.E.S.S. on 2013 March 6 to March 10 show no significant changes in the flux. They limit the variation on the integral flux above 1 TeV to less than 63% and the integral flux above 5 TeV to less than 78% at a 95% confidence level.'), (u'author', [OrderedDict([(u'@nr', u'1'), (u'name', OrderedDict([(u'western', u'H. OrderedDict([(u'@bibcode', u'2000Icar..146..541S'), (u'metadata', [OrderedDict([(u'@origin', u'AP; ELSEVIER'), (u'@type', u'general'), (u'@primary', u'True'), (u'@alternate_journal', u'False'), (u'creation_time', u'2014-02-06T21:55:51'), (u'modification_time', u'2014-02-06T21:55:51'), (u'bibcode', u'2000Icar..146..541S'), (u'dates', OrderedDict([(u'date', OrderedDict([(u'@type', u'date-published'), ('#text', u'2000-08-00')]))])), (u'title', u'Nereid Has Complex Large-Amplitude Photometric Variability'), (u'abstract', u"We report on 224 photometric measurements of Nereid, a small outer satellite of Neptune with a 360-day orbit of high eccentricity (0.751). Our photometry covers 64 nights from 1987 to 1997 and is primarily in the V-band, although we also have 20 measurements in the U, B, R, and I bands. (1) Nereid displays large-amplitude brightness variations with a total amplitude of 1.83 mag on time scales ranging from a few hours to roughly a year. (2) During the 12 days of the Voyager encounter with Neptune, Nereid did not display any short-term variations; however, large-amplitude long-term variations could easily be hidden by the large phase effects and the short duration of observation. (3) Nereid's variability is caused by high contrast albedo features, i.e., a dark hemisphere, along with rotational modulation. (4) The character of the brightness variations changed around 1991 from fast and large-amplitude to comparatively slow and low-amplitude. This demonstrates that the direction and magnitude of Nereid's rotational angular momentum vector is changing on time scales comparable to its orbital period. (5) Large changes in the magnitude and direction of Nereid's angular momentum vector are predicted to arise from chaotic rotation during every periapse passage provided that Nereid is more than \u03031% nonspherical and is spinning slowly. The match between prediction and observation could be taken as strong evidence for chaotic rotation of Nereid. However, the intranight variability cannot be readily explained by chaotic rotation. (6) The colors of Nereid are U-V=0.84\xb10.05, B-V=0.71\xb10.04, V-R=0.44\xb10.03, V-I=0.72\xb10.05, and V-K=1.6, indicating a nearly flat reflectance spectrum from 0.36 to 2.2 \u03bcm. We identify asteroids, inner satellites, and centaurs with similar spectra. (7) Nereid is likely either an inner moon of Neptune kicked to its current orbit or a captured Kuiper Belt object or centaur, with the latter possibility being strongly preferred."), (u'author', u'date-preprint'), ('#text', u'2000-05-00')]))])), (u'title', u'Nereid Has Complex Large-Amplitude Photometric Variability (Due to Chaotic Rotation)'), (u'abstract', u"We report on 224 photometric measurements of Nereid, a small outer satellite of Neptune. Our photometry covers 64 nights from 1987 to 1997 and is primarily in the V-band; we also have 20 measurements in the U, B, R, and I bands. (1) Nereid displays large-amplitude brightness variations with a total amplitude of 1.83 mag on time scales ranging from a few hours to roughly a year. (2) The amplitude as well as the time scale of variation changes greatly from year to year. (3) Nereid's variability is caused by high contrast albedo features along with rotational modulation. (4) The changing amplitudes and time scales demonstrate that the direction and magnitude of Nereid's rotational angular momentum vector is not constant. (5) Such changes are predicted to arise from chaotic rotation during every periapse passage provided that Nereid is more than about 1% nonspherical and is spinning slowly. The match between prediction and observation could be taken as strong evidence for chaotic rotation of Nereid. However, the intranight variability cannot be readily explained by chaotic rotation. (6) The colors of Nereid are U-V=0.84+-0.05, B-V=0.71+-0.04, V-R=0.44+-0.03, V-I=0.72+-0.05, and V-K=1.6. (7) Nereid is likely either an inner moon of Neptune kicked to its current orbit or a captured Kuiper Belt Object or centaur, with the latter possibility being strongly preferred."), (u'author', [OrderedDict([(u'@nr', u'1'), (u'name', OrderedDict([(u'western', u'Schaefer, Bradley E.'), (u'normalized', u'Schaefer, B')])), (u'type', u'regular')]), OrderedDict([(u'@nr', u'2'), (u'name', OrderedDict([(u'western', u'Schaefer, Martha W.'), (u'normalized', u'Schaefer, M')])), (u'type', u'regular')])]), (u'journal', u'eprint arXiv:astro-ph/0005050'), (u'page_range', u'5050'), (u'canonical_journal', u'ArXiv e-prints'), (u'publication_year', u'2000'), (u'page', u'5050'), (u'arxivcategories', OrderedDict([(u'arxivcategory', OrderedDict([(u'@type', u'main'), ('#text', u'Astrophysics')]))])), (u'keywords', OrderedDict([(u'@type', u'arXiv'), (u'keyword', OrderedDict([(u'@channel', u'astro-ph'), (u'original', u'Astrophysics'), (u'normalized', u'astrophysics')]))])), (u'comment', OrderedDict([(u'@origin', u'ADS'), ('#text', u'Icarus, in press. 20 pages, 9 figures; OrderedDict([(u'date', OrderedDict([(u'@type', u'date-preprint'), ('#text', u'2010-02-00')]))])), (u'title', u'The Spectrum of the Isotropic Diffuse Gamma-Ray Emission Derived From First-Year Fermi Large Area Telescope Data'), (u'abstract', u'We report on the first Fermi Large Area Telescope (LAT) measurements of the so-called "extra-galactic" diffuse gamma-ray emission (EGB). This component of the diffuse gamma-ray emission is generally considered to have an isotropic or nearly isotropic distribution on the sky with diverse contributions discussed in the literature. The derivation of the EGB is based on detailed modelling of the bright foreground diffuse Galactic gamma-ray emission (DGE), the detected LAT sources and the solar gamma-ray emission. We find the spectrum of the EGB is consistent with a power law with differential spectral index g = 2.41+/-0.05 and intensity, I(> 100 MeV) = (1.03+/-0.17) 10^-5 cm^-2 s^-1 sr^-1, where the error is systematics dominated. Our EGB spectrum is featureless, less intense, and softer than that derived from EGRET data.'), (u'author', OrderedDict([(u'@nr', u'1'), (u'name', OrderedDict([(u'western', u'The Fermi-LAT collaboration'), (u'normalized', u'The Fermi-LAT collaboration')])), (u'type', u'regular')])), (u'journal', u'eprint arXiv:1002.3603'), (u'page_range', u'3603'), (u'canonical_journal', u'ArXiv e-prints'), (u'publication_year', u'2010'), (u'page', u'3603'), (u'arxivcategories', OrderedDict([(u'arxivcategory', [OrderedDict([(u'@type', u'main'), ('#text', u'Astrophysics - High Energy Astrophysical Phenomena')]), u'Astrophysics - Cosmology and Extragalactic Astrophysics'])])), (u'keywords', OrderedDict([(u'@type', u'arXiv'), (u'keyword', [OrderedDict([(u'@channel', u'astro-ph.HE'), (u'original', u'Astrophysics - High Energy Astrophysical Phenomena'), (u'normalized', None)]), OrderedDict([(u'@channel', u'astro-ph.CO'), (u'original', u'Astrophysics - Cosmology and Extragalactic Astrophysics'), (u'normalized', None)])])])), (u'comment', OrderedDict([(u'@origin', u'ADS'), ('#text', u'4 figures, 1 table, supplementary material, accepted by Physical Review Letters; III - NGC 3998'), (u'abstract', u'Synthesis observations of H I in the active S0 galaxy NGC 3998 show that the gas is in a polar ring, inclined about 80\xb0 to the optical major axis. The position angle of the ionized gas in the inner galaxy is intermediate between those of H I and the light, suggesting differential precession of the gas structure. Weak extensions on the radio continuum emission from the nucleus are roughly perpendicular to the inner gas distribution. The circular velocity derived from the H I is normal for a galaxy of this luminosity; however, the ratio of central bulge velocity dispersion to circular velocity is anomalously high. Further, gasdynamical models for M 81 are presented and compared with high-resolution H-line observations. These measurements, in conjunction with other cosmological probes including observations of supernova, galaxy surveys, and additional local measurements of the Hubble constant, have contributed crucial evidence for the cosmological model known as LCDM. Upcoming generations of CMB instruments are poised to constrain additional models that describe the properties of the Universe when it was < 1e-34 seconds old and improve our understanding of large scale structure formation. OrderedDict([(u'@bibcode', u'2002JGRA..107.1012N'), (u'metadata', [OrderedDict([(u'@origin', u'AGU'), (u'@type', u'general'), (u'@primary', u'True'), (u'@alternate_journal', u'False'), (u'creation_time', u'2011-10-04T17:07:05'), (u'modification_time', u'2011-10-04T17:07:05'), (u'bibcode', u'2002JGRA..107.1012N'), (u'dates', OrderedDict([(u'date', OrderedDict([(u'@type', u'date-published'), ('#text', u'2002-01-00')]))])), (u'title', u'VHF coherent radar signals from the E region ionosphere and the relationship to electron drift velocity and ion acoustic velocity'), (u'abstract', u'The Scandinavian Twin Auroral Radar Experiment (STARE) coherent radar system measures the Doppler shifts caused by ~1 m plasma waves in the high-latitude E region ionosphere. These Doppler velocities are here related to the electron drift velocity and ion acoustic velocity derived from measurements with the incoherent radar system European Incoherent Scatter (EISCAT). The Doppler velocity is limited in magnitude to near the ion acoustic velocity in the plasma. For large flow angles \u03b8, i.e., the angle between the radar line of sight and the electron drift velocity, the Doppler shifts are equal to the component of the electron drift velocity on the line of sight. For \u03b8 ~ 40\xb0 the Doppler velocity is equal to the ion acoustic velocity at 105-km altitude, and for decreasing flow angle the Doppler velocity increases. For 0\xb0 < \u03b8 < 60\xb0 the variation with flow angle can be described as cos<SUP>\u03b1</SUP>\u03b8, where the \u03b1 decreases from 0.8 to 0.2 with an increase in drift speed from ~400 to 1600 ms<SUP>-1</SUP>. The ratio of the line-of-sight velocity for \u03b8 ~ 0\xb0 to the ion acoustic velocity decreases from 1.2 at low velocities to 1.05 at large velocities. The systematic variations of the Doppler shifts with drift speed and flow angle make it possible, in principle, to recover the electron velocity from the coherent radar measurements. OrderedDict([(u'@bibcode', u'1986PhRvA..33.2281B'), (u'metadata', [OrderedDict([(u'@origin', u'STI'), (u'@type', u'general'), (u'@primary', u'True'), (u'@alternate_journal', u'False'), (u'creation_time', u'2013-12-05T03:49:26'), (u'modification_time', u'2013-12-05T03:49:26'), (u'bibcode', u'1986PhRvA..33.2281B'), (u'dates', OrderedDict([(u'date', OrderedDict([(u'@type', u'date-published'), ('#text', u'1986-04-00')]))])), (u'title', u'Direct-annihilation fraction of positrons in a neutral low-density galactic environment'), (u'abstract', u'The fraction of positrons which survive below the positronium (Ps) formation energy in a low-density galactic environment can directly annihilate with bound electrons in the gas. The details of the measurement of the survival (direct-annihilation) fraction using a low-energy laboratory positron beam are presented for H2 and H3. The fraction is found to be higher in H2 than had been predicted by Bussard, Ramaty, and Drachman (1979). The galactic positron line has been shown to be consistent with the line shape expected for annihilation in a neutral medium based on this measurement and on a theoretical prediction of the direct-annihilation linewidth.'), (u'author', [OrderedDict([(u'@nr', u'1'), (u'name', OrderedDict([(u'western', u'Brown, B. OrderedDict([(u'@bibcode', u'1996MNRAS.281L..35W'), (u'metadata', [OrderedDict([(u'@origin', u'ARI; MNRAS'), (u'@type', u'general'), (u'@primary', u'True'), (u'@alternate_journal', u'False'), (u'creation_time', u'2011-11-16T10:09:31'), (u'modification_time', u'2011-11-16T10:09:31'), (u'bibcode', u'1996MNRAS.281L..35W'), (u'dates', OrderedDict([(u'date', OrderedDict([(u'@type', u'date-published'), ('#text', u'1996-08-00')]))])), (u'title', u'The giant protogalaxy cB 58: an artefact of gravitational lensing?'), (u'abstract', u'The protogalaxy cB58 was discovered in the Canadian Network of Observational Cosmology (CNOC) survey of cluster redshifts. Absorption features reveal that this system is at a redshift of z = 2.72, implying an absolute magnitude of M<SUB>V</SUB> \u2261 -26, and has a star formation rate of 4700 M<SUB>sun</SUB>yr<SUP>-1</SUP>, making it the most "active" star-forming galaxy. This protogalaxy is observed to lie close (\u22616 arcsec) to a central cluster galaxy at z = 0.373. The X-ray properties of the cluster suggest that its mass, and therefore its lensing potential, could be greater than that found using a virial analysis. Here, the authors argue that the phenomenal properties of this protogalaxy are due to the gravitational lensing effect of the foreground cluster, and the unlensed properties of the source are typical of high-redshift star-forming systems.'), (u'author', [OrderedDict([(u'@nr', u'1'), (u'name', OrderedDict([(u'western', u'Williams, L. OrderedDict([(u'@bibcode', u'2014ApJ...784L..17L'), (u'metadata', [OrderedDict([(u'@origin', u'IOP'), (u'@type', u'general'), (u'@primary', u'True'), (u'@alternate_journal', u'False'), (u'creation_time', u'2014-05-15T17:43:22'), (u'modification_time', u'2014-05-15T17:43:22'), (u'bibcode', u'2014ApJ...784L..17L'), (u'dates', OrderedDict([(u'date', OrderedDict([(u'@type', u'date-published'), ('#text', u'2014-03-00')]))])), (u'title', u'The Effect of Isotopic Splitting on the Bisector and Inversions of the Solar Ca II 854.2 nm Line'), (u'abstract', u'The Ca II 854.2 nm spectral line is a common diagnostic of the solar chromosphere. The average line profile shows an asymmetric core, and its bisector shows a characteristic inverse-C shape. The line actually consists of six components with slightly different wavelengths depending on the isotope of calcium. This isotopic splitting of the line has been taken into account in studies of non-solar stars, but never for the Sun. We performed non-LTE radiative transfer computations from three models of the solar atmosphere and show that the line-core asymmetry and inverse C-shape of the bisector of the 854.2 nm line can be explained by isotopic splitting. We confirm this finding by analyzing observations and showing that the line asymmetry is present irrespective of conditions in the solar atmosphere. Finally, we show that inversions based on the Ca II 854.2 nm line should take the isotopic splitting into account, otherwise the inferred atmospheres will contain erroneous velocity gradients and temperatures.'), (u'author', [OrderedDict([(u'@nr', u'1'), (u'name', OrderedDict([(u'western', u'Leenaarts, Jorrit'), (u'normalized', u'Leenaarts, J')])), (u'affiliations', OrderedDict([(u'affiliation', u'Institute of Theoretical Astrophysics, University of Oslo, P.O. The average line profile shows an asymmetric core, and its bisector shows a characteristic inverse-C shape. The line actually consists of six components with slightly different wavelengths depending on the isotope of calcium. This isotopic splitting of the line has been taken into account in studies of non-solar stars, but never for the Sun. We performed non-LTE radiative transfer computations from three models of the solar atmosphere and show that the asymmetric line-core and inverse C-shape of the bisector of the 854.2 nm line can be explained by isotopic splitting. We confirm this finding by analysing observations and showing that the line asymmetry is present irrespective of conditions in the solar atmosphere. Finally, we show that inversions based on the Ca II 854.2 nm line should take the isotopic splitting into account, otherwise the inferred atmospheres will contain erroneous velocity gradients and temperatures.'), (u'author', [OrderedDict([(u'@nr', u'1'), (u'name', OrderedDict([(u'western', u'Leenaarts, Jorrit'), (u'normalized', u'Leenaarts, J')])), (u'type', u'regular')]), OrderedDict([(u'@nr', u'2'), (u'name', OrderedDict([(u'western', u'de la Cruz Rodr\xedguez, Jaime'), (u'normalized', u'de la Cruz Rodriguez, J')])), (u'type', u'regular')]), OrderedDict([(u'@nr', u'3'), (u'name', OrderedDict([(u'western', u'Kochukhov, Oleg'), (u'normalized', u'Kochukhov, O')])), (u'type', u'regular')]), OrderedDict([(u'@nr', u'4'), (u'name', OrderedDict([(u'western', u'Carlsson, Mats'), (u'normalized', u'Carlsson, M')])), (u'type', u'regular')])]), (u'journal', u'eprint arXiv:1401.5019'), (u'page_range', u'5019'), (u'canonical_journal', u'ArXiv e-prints'), (u'publication_year', u'2014'), (u'page', u'5019'), (u'arxivcategories', OrderedDict([(u'arxivcategory', OrderedDict([(u'@type', u'main'), ('#text', u'Astrophysics - OrderedDict([(u'@bibcode', u'1986PhDT.........1A'), (u'metadata', [OrderedDict([(u'@origin', u'UMI'), (u'@type', u'general'), (u'@primary', u'False'), (u'@alternate_journal', u'False'), (u'creation_time', u'2012-07-12T13:52:42'), (u'modification_time', u'2012-07-12T13:52:42'), (u'bibcode', u'1986PhDT.........1A'), (u'dates', OrderedDict([(u'date', OrderedDict([(u'@type', u'date-thesis'), ('#text', u'1986-00-00')]))])), (u'title', u'Problems in Quantum Cosmology.'), (u'abstract', u'The standard cosmological model is reviewed and shown not to be self-sufficient in that it requires initial conditions which are most likely to be supplied by quantum cosmology. The possible approaches to the issue of initial conditions for cosmology are then discussed. In this thesis, I shall consider three separate problems related to this issue. First, the possibility of inflation is investigated in detail by analyzing the evolution of metric perturbations and fluctuations in the expectation value of a scalar field prior to a phase transition; finite temperature effects are also included. Since the inhomogeneities were damped well before the onset of a phase transition, I conclude that an inflation was possible. Next, the effective action of neutrino and photon fields is calculated for homogeneous spacetimes with small anisotropy, and is shown that quantum corrections to the action due to these fields influence the evolution of an early Universe in the same way as do the analogous correction terms arising from a conformally invariant scalar which has been previously studied. I thus conclude that the physical processes of neutrino and photon production could rapidly dissipate any anisotropy in an early Universe. In addition, I have extended the scalar field calculations to finite temperature, where it is shown that the probability of the particle production is enhanced. Contrary to the T = 0 case, though, finite temperature necessitates the consideration of the nonlocal term in the action. Finally, the question of an early anisotropy is also discussed in a framework of Hartle-Hawking "wave function of the Universe". A wave function of a Bianchi IX type Universe is calculated in a semiclassical approximation for a model with a cosmological constant, and by solving the Wheeler-DeWitt equation numerically for a model with classical radiation. It is shown that an anisotropic Universe is very unlikely, and that the expectation value of the anisotropy energy density decreases very fast as the Universe expands.'), (u'author', OrderedDict([(u'@nr', u'1'), (u'name', OrderedDict([(u'western', u'Amsterdamski, Piotr'), (u'normalized', u'Amsterdamski, P')])), (u'affiliations', OrderedDict([(u'affiliation', u'UNIVERSITY OF CALIFORNIA, SANTA BARBARA.')])), (u'type', u'regular')])), (u'ADSaffiliation', u'AA(UNIVERSITY OF CALIFORNIA, SANTA BARBARA.)'), (u'journal', u'Thesis (PH.D.)--UNIVERSITY OF CALIFORNIA, SANTA BARBARA, 1986.Source: Dissertation Abstracts International,  Volume: 47-09, Section: B, page: 3810.'), (u'canonical_journal', u'Ph.D. Thesis'), (u'publication_year', u'1986'), (u'electronic_id', u's International,  Volume: 47-09, Section: B, page: 3810'), (u'keywords', OrderedDict([(u'@type', u'STI category'), (u'keyword', OrderedDict([(u'@channel', u''), (u'original', u'Physics: Astronomy and Astrophysics'), (u'normalized', None)]))]))]), OrderedDict([(u'@origin', u'STI'), (u'@type', u'general'), (u'@primary', u'True'), (u'@alternate_journal', u'False'), (u'creation_time', u'2013-12-05T03:49:22'), (u'modification_time', u'2013-12-05T03:49:22'), (u'bibcode', u'1986PhDT.........1A'), (u'dates', OrderedDict([(u'date', OrderedDict([(u'@type', u'date-thesis'), ('#text', u'1986-00-00')]))])), (u'title', u'Problems in quantum cosmology'), (u'abstract', u'The standard cosmological model is reviewed and shown not to be self-sufficient in that it requires initial conditions which are most likely to be supplied by quantum cosmology.
